    public interface IFIXMessageSpecifics
extends IRepeatingGroupAccessor, Cloneable, IMessage, ILoggerContext
    Defines the FIX specific methods in IFIXMessage - ie all methods which do not appear in the generic ITagValues interface, or in IFIXMessage itself.

      • addEncodedField

        void addEncodedField(int tag,
                     String value)
              throws BadDataExceptionWithCode
        Adds an encoded field preceded by its associated length field.

        This is a utility method. It does nothing that you could not do yourself using the basic methods. The advantage of using this method is that it reduces the risk of mistakes.

        This method does the following:

        • Confirms that tag is for an encoded field
        • Gets length field tag associated with the encoded field tag
        • Confirms that messageEncoded has been set for this message
        • Creates encoded field object from tag and value
        • Create the associated length field object set to appropriate length
        • Associates length field with encoded field
        • Adds length field to message's fields, immediately followed by encoded field

        Valid encoding must be set on this message or it will throw exception.

        Parameters:
        tag - Tag of field to be added
        value - Value of field to be added
        Throws:
        BadDataExceptionWithCode - if tag is not an encoded field or if message encoding has not been set

        void setDecrypter(Crypto decrypter,
                  boolean dialectAllowNoLengthOnRawData)
           throws MessageIntegrityException
        Set decrypter object and triggers decryption of the message.
        Parameters:

        dialectAllowNoLengthOnRawData - True to indicate that no special treatment is to be given to raw data and their associated length fields (that is, they are expected to conform to regular FIX field content and in particular the data field should not contain FIX SOH), false to treat the data field as opaque and use its preceding length field to determine its length.

      • setValue

        void setValue(int tag,
              Date value,
              boolean isDate,
              TimeZone timeZone,
              boolean useMilliseconds)
        Sets the field's value to the time expressed in the given time zone formatted either as a FIX date or time depending on isDate.

        For example, to format the current time as local time: 

         setValue(tag, new Date(), false, TimeZone.getDefault(), false);
        To format the current time as USA Eastern Standard Time: 
         setValue(tag, new Date(), false, TimeZone.getTimeZone("EST"), false);

        If the field appears more than once, only one instance will be set.
        If the field does not exist, it is added.

        If a field is added and it is an encoded field and there is already a field present which specifies an encoding method, then the field's encoding method is set to the specified method.

        Parameters:
        tag - Tag of field to change.
        value - Date/Time to be formatted into the field as a String.
        isDate - Formats as a FIX date or FIX date/time accordingly.
        timeZone - TimeZone in which time is to be expressed. GMT (UTC) if null.
        useMilliseconds - whether or not to specify milliseconds on the date.

      • setUseExactFixDictionary

        void setUseExactFixDictionary(boolean useExactFixDictionary)
        Set attribute to control whether session dictionary should be used when importing raw FIX bytes. By default the session will use the dictionary of the latest version of FIX when importing raw FIX bytes. This allows users to use fields from later versions of FIX in sessions configured to use earlier FIX versions. Set this value to true if you would like to use the dictionary of the FIX version of this session. You might need to do this if you use custom fields in your messages that are defined differently by a later version of the FIX protocol.
        Parameters:
        useExactFixDictionary - true or false; default is false

      • getUseExactFixDictionary

        boolean getUseExactFixDictionary()
        Return the attribute which control whether session dictionary should be used when importing raw FIX bytes.
        Returns:
        true or false; default is false
        See Also:
        setUseExactFixDictionary(boolean)
